00:39:14.190 --> 00:39:18.770
admit it? Can I say it? Think of senior people
that

00:39:18.770 --> 00:39:20.950
you work with that do that. What do you think
of them?

00:39:20.950 --> 00:39:24.090
I think your first reaction is "Wow, this
person's

00:39:24.090 --> 00:39:29.350
really good." I think it's impressive. Whereas
we tend

00:39:29.350 --> 00:39:30.901
to think when we admit these things, I'm going
to look

00:39:30.901 --> 00:39:33.860
like a weakling or I'm going to look like
I'm not very

00:39:33.860 --> 00:39:37.211
good. And what I'm trying to say to people
is, our

00:39:37.211 --> 00:39:40.160
conventional stereotypes of leaders, I don't
think

00:39:40.160 --> 00:39:43.320
they're right. I think the truth is -- that's
with the

00:39:43.320 --> 00:39:47.020
whole premise of this book. When I say it's
more important

00:39:47.020 --> 00:39:48.800
to ask the right question, I don't think that's
our

00:39:48.800 --> 00:39:52.740
stereotype of leaders who are, you know, giving
orders

00:39:52.740 --> 00:39:54.830
or a President of the United States saying
I'm the

00:39:54.830 --> 00:39:57.690
decider. Yeah, sometimes that's true, but
you've got to

00:39:57.690 --> 00:40:01.080
be willing to admit what you don't know, build
your team

00:40:01.080 --> 00:40:02.990
accordingly, understand your strengths and
weaknesses,

00:40:02.990 --> 00:40:05.460
get advice, and I think you're going to be
dramatically

00:40:05.460 --> 00:40:12.710
more effective. Are you being yourself? Those
little -- Alana was showing me the red dots,

00:40:12.710 --> 00:40:15.850
and the
green, and about the food. I mean, so you

00:40:15.850 --> 00:40:18.241
got to watch
what you're eating, know the calories. Let's

00:40:18.241 --> 00:40:20.890
all say
it. I want you the feel like this is your

00:40:20.890 --> 00:40:24.740
company that
we care about you that you can be yourself.

00:40:24.740 --> 00:40:27.611
The problem
is, no matter how much the company does, some

00:40:27.611 --> 00:40:30.110
of it's
got to come from you, and this gets back to

00:40:30.110 --> 00:40:32.580
the trust
issue. And the one that I'm most interested

00:40:32.580 --> 00:40:39.051
in is these
last two. Are you willing to confront, speak

00:40:39.051 --> 00:40:42.600
up,
disagree? And I'm not a troublemaker, but

00:40:42.600 --> 00:40:46.770
there are
times where if you just think your boss, or

00:40:46.770 --> 00:40:49.520
the company,
or your peers are about to make a terrible

00:40:49.520 --> 00:40:53.770
mistake, are
you willing to say, you know, "I don't think

00:40:53.770 --> 00:40:55.310
I
understand what we're doing. I don't think

00:40:55.310 --> 00:40:58.650
I agree."
Understanding -- you may be wrong, they may

00:40:58.650 --> 00:41:01.880
beat your
brains in and make you feel dumb, but the

00:41:01.880 --> 00:41:04.650
occasionally
got to do this I would argue as a leader.

00:41:04.650 --> 00:41:07.180
This is the
essence of leadership. And there are some

00:41:07.180 --> 00:41:10.640
people that
are so politically correct that it just -- you

00:41:10.640 --> 00:41:12.920
know,
they think it's rude, or you know there's

00:41:12.920 --> 00:41:16.450
lots of
reasons to talk yourself out of this but my

00:41:16.450 --> 00:41:18.960
experience
is, you're going to be much more likely to

00:41:18.960 --> 00:41:23.200
reach your
potential if you're yourself. And by the way,

00:41:23.200 --> 00:41:26.540
I am
certain this company and companies generally

00:41:26.540 --> 00:41:29.840
will do
dramatically better. The bigger the group

00:41:29.840 --> 00:41:32.680
of people
that feel comfortable being themselves so

00:41:32.680 --> 00:41:34.951
they can
assert themselves, you're going to have a

00:41:34.951 --> 00:41:39.000
far more
successful enterprise. So let me stop there.

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:40.530
That's
really all this book is about. And all I'm

00:41:40.530 --> 00:41:43.750
suggesting -- there's a lot more, obviously,
in the book

00:41:43.750 --> 00:41:47.570
than this, but this is the thumbnail. Keep
five or six

00:41:47.570 --> 00:41:49.920
questions on your wall. If you don't like
these ones ,

00:41:49.920 --> 00:41:52.910
pick two or three others, but I think you've
got to --

00:41:52.910 --> 00:41:55.990
when you're in trouble, which I get a raft
of people

00:41:55.990 --> 00:42:00.350
come into my office or phone calls at Morgan
Hall when

00:42:00.350 --> 00:42:03.360
they're struggling, at all levels: Former
students all

00:42:03.360 --> 00:42:06.750
the way up to CEOs of companies, governors
of -- you

00:42:06.750 --> 00:42:10.670
know, governors, public officials, all with
the same

00:42:10.670 --> 00:42:13.560
point. I'm having a problem. And usually what
I do is

00:42:13.560 --> 00:42:16.670
go through a series of questions with them.
All I'm

00:42:16.670 --> 00:42:19.900
saying, have four or five questions on your
